posts.com:
IMF Raises Global Growth Forecast for this Year, but Revises South Korea Downward...South Korea's Weaknesses as Seen by IMF
1/31 (Tue) 13:31

JoongAng Ilbo

The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has raised its forecast for global economic
growth this year from 2.7% to 2.9%, but it has revised its forecast for the ROK
downward from 2.0% to 1.7%. Despite the reopening of China, the aftermath of the
semiconductor export shock will limit the positive effect on Korea's economy.

According to the Ministry of Strategy and Finance, in its World Economic Outlook (WEO)
released on the same day, the IMF put the projected economic growth rate for the ROK
at 1.7% this year. This is 0.3 percentage points lower than the previous forecast (2.0%)
that came out last October. This is the third consecutive time that the IMF has made
a downward adjustment to its forecast, following its July announcement of 2.9% to 2.1%
and its October announcement of 2.1% to 2.0%.

On the other hand, the IMF raised its forecast for global economic growth this year from
2.7% to 2.9%. It cited China's reopening expectations and unexpectedly strong consumption
and investment in the U.S., Europe, and other major economies as the basis for the ncrease,
despite the interest rate hike to cope with inflation and the war between Russia and Ucraine.

The growth forecast for major advanced economies was raised by 0.1 percentage point
to 1.2%. The forecast for the U.S. growth rate was revised upward from 1.0% to 1.4%,
and that for the euro zone from 0.5% to 0.7%. China raised its forecast by 0.8
percentage point, from 4.4% to 5.2%.

Orbán még az ételt sem tiszteli - a falhoz vágott mákos bejgli esete

Orbán Viktor nem volt könnyen kezelhető gyerek. Szigorú, konok, durva apja és nagyapja olyan mintákat közvetítettek számára, hogy nem is lehetett jóravaló, széplelkű és finom. Az iskolában is sokat küzdöttek nehéz természetével, a tanárai és a diáktársai is.

Még általános iskolában történt az eset, hogy a normál ebéden túl lehetőség volt repetát kérni a mákos bejgliből. Kivéve Orbán Viktornak, akit a tanár eltiltott a repetától, mert rosszul viselkedett. Viktorka erre megbízott egy másik gyereket, hogy álljon sorba és szerezzen neki mákos bejglit. A gyerek megtette, amit Viktorka kért, majd rendelkezésére bocsátotta a sütiszeletet. A tanárnő ezt észrevette, számon kérte a gyermek Orbánt, aki erre hangos vitába keveredett a tanerővel. Végül a mákos bejglit a falhoz vágta, a következő mondattal: "Itt van, nesze!”.

Voltaképpen nem tett semmi mást, mint amit ma is: demonstrálta a tisztelet teljes hiányát, a tanár, a diáktársa és ami a legsúlyosabb, az étel felé. Ma is ugyanezt teszi, ha valami nem tetszik neki - falhoz vágja. Ugyanez a dühös, kezelhetetlen gyerek lakozik most is a miniszterelnök lelkében. Nem változott, nem fejlődött.

Egy hatalommániás, kezelhetetlen, szélsőséges embernek adtunk hatalmat. Miért hagyjuk, hogy a falhoz csapkodjon?

posts.com:
>>177659002
>Ő New Yorkból.
(Ő) New Yorkból származik.
Or you could say "New York-i." This means "New Yorker" but with enough context you can use it in a conversation. For example:
-Hova valósi?
-New York-i.

>Seinfeld egy befolyásos műsor.
A Seinfeld egy ikonikus műsor. "Befolyásos" means impactful, I don't think it's really used in this context. Also you need a definite article in this case when you are talking about an exact work of art (unless the work of art itself begins with a definite article)

>Ő Seinfeldt Larry Daviddel együtt csinált.
Larry Daviddel együtt csinálta/készítette a Seinfeldet. Or: "A Seinfeldet Larry Daviddel együtt csinálta/készítette."
Remember that with enough context provided, Hungarian is a pro-drop language, so you can omit "ő" since we know that we are talking about Seinfeld.
Furthermore, the reason why it's "Seinfeldet" and not "Seinfeldt" is because you need that vowel in front of the direct object ending to help with pronunciation. If you have a word that ends in a consonant you will most likely use -et, -ot or -öt to denote a direct object, instead of -t.
And the reason why it's "csinálta" and not "csinált" is because you are talking about a definite thing, not just any thing.
For example:
Csinált egy filmet. He was making a movie.
Csinálta a filmet. He was making the movie.

Overall you are coming along nicely anon, good job.

>>177658685
>Duolingo
It's useless beyond alphabet learning, if not harmful.

>Pushkin Institute
Never heard of it. I guess some trivia games are alright.

If you want to learn the casual language, or have a solid base for the language, go for anime with subtitles (you can find a lot of Russian .srt's for anime and movies on torrents).
The trick with the language is that you have to learn faster than you forget it. The forgetting pattern is described by Ebbinghaus curve.

So you have to binge the most basic language for 2 weeks to give you a proper start with it.
But you'd be bored to death with cards. And duolingo won't make it less boring with it's faggotry.
Solution for this is: anime, hollywood.
Anything you don't get pause and look in the dictionary (google, yandex, multitran, context reverso), image search or wikipedia cross-references.

Ofc Hollywood experience would not be proper, if you watch it in English, as you already know it, and instead of learning Russians from subs you'd just repeat English.

Another way is if you really like books - read your favorite books in Russian. Again, there's a lot of them on torrents.

After 2 weeks/4h daily crash course, you can step up and start listening the language. Audiobooks, YT lectures or just various clowns.

>pronounciation
Not important and hardly possible imo. Find some ways if you want to sound native, other than I've described.

posts.com: Ilhabela (Portuguese for Beautiful Island) is an archipelago and city situated in the Atlantic Ocean six kilometres (4 miles) off the coast of São Paulo state in Brazil. The city is 205km (127mi) from the city of São Paulo. The largest island, although commonly called Ilhabela, is officially named Ilha de São Sebastião (St. Sebastian Island). The first documented non-indigenous visit to the island was an expedition involving Italian cosmographer Amerigo Vespucci that arrived there on 20 January 1502. As with several other geographical features discovered by the Portuguese, the island was named after the saint of the day (Saint Sebastian).[7] Around that time, the island would provide shelter for pirates and corsairs coming mainly from England, France and the Netherlands. Most of the city has a tropical climate, but the mountains have an oceanic climate, because of the high altitude. The Atlantic Forest covers the entire city. The fauna and flora in Ilhabela prompted the government to create the Ilhabela State Park, The park's importance made it be considered a bioshpere reserve by UNESCO.

posts.com: Ilha da Queimada Grande, also known as Snake Island, is an island off the coast of Brazil in the Atlantic Ocean. It is administered as part of the municipality of Itanhaém in the State of São Paulo. The island is small in size, only 43 hectares (106 acres), and has a temperate climate. The snakes became trapped on the island thousands of years ago following the end of the last ice age when rising ocean levels disconnected the island from the mainland. The ensuing evolutionary pressure allowed the snakes to adapt to their new environment, increasing rapidly in population and rendering the island dangerous to public visitation. Because there are so many snakes on one island — by some estimates one snake to every square meter (10.8 square feet) — there is competition for resources. The island was previously thought to have a population of about 430,000 snakes, but recent estimates are much lower.

Abbreviations are a derivative of a loanword and are meaningless in the absence thereof, so yes, they also count as loanwords. posts.com:
relatively few (100-120k) words as a linguistic core but those have 3-400k definitions. You can be fluent starting 60k or so using these layered definitions well. analogy, small talk and idioms are much more necessary to set the tone of a conversation and focused, tight vocabulary lists make it easy to "bob and weave".
same same but different for italian, 200k words will make you fluent and then some but recombination and a wide net of "sayable" or "writable" words give those half a million or more possible meanings.
German on the other hand uses much the same 200-300k words it has since the 15th century with minor adjustments for pronounciation and you need most if not all of those to be fluent. Once you got those however they can be used very precisely and don't need much context.
